            "html": "<p class=\"q-text qu-display--block qu-wordBreak--break-word qu-textAlign--start\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 1em; overflow-wrap: anywhere; direction: ltr;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">Absolutely.  It will be a while before they are legal for regular people though.  </span></p> <p class=\"q-text qu-display--block qu-wordBreak--break-word qu-textAlign--start\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 1em; overflow-wrap: anywhere; direction: ltr;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">If safety is the concern, well, that's what statistics are for.  By the time regular people can use them, there should be plenty of  stats out there as to how many crashes there have been, and you can use that to predict whether it is safer than other activities you might do.  I don't base such safety decisions on pure intuition, or some attempt to do armchair engineering on it....I mean, by that way of looking at it, airplanes seem pretty unsafe.  But I know that the great majority of airplanes that go up, come down safely.  Statistics says flying is safer than driving.  So I will get into a plane.  Same here.</span></p> <p class=\"q-text qu-display--block qu-wordBreak--break-word qu-textAlign--start\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 1em; overflow-wrap: anywhere; direction: ltr;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">Now, as to why I look forward to having self-driving cars.  The main way they will be cool will be making car ownership unnecessary.  You need a car?  Tap a button on your phone, and one drive itself to you.  When you get where you are going, just get out and let it drive away.  Here in San Francisco, parking is a huge pain, you can spend 10 minutes driving somewhere and then half an hour finding a place to park and then walking from that place.</span></p> <p class=\"q-text qu-display--block qu-wordBreak--break-word qu-textAlign--start\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 0px; overflow-wrap: anywhere; direction: ltr;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">You can do that with a cab, but you are having to pay for a human driver, and that's a lot more expensive.  Self driving cars will make it much more feasable to not own a car, or to have neighborhood car sharing.  The end result is we could have a whole lot less cars, since the ones that exist will be in use most of the time rather than sitting there parked taking up space.</span></p>",
            "content": "Absolutely.  It will be a while before they are legal for regular people though.   If safety is the concern, well, that's what statistics are for.  By the time regular people can use them, there should be plenty of  stats out there as to how many crashes there have been, and you can use that to predict whether it is safer than other activities you might do.  I don't base such safety decisions on pure intuition, or some attempt to do armchair engineering on it....I mean, by that way of looking at it, airplanes seem pretty unsafe.  But I know that the great majority of airplanes that go up, come down safely.  Statistics says flying is safer than driving.  So I will get into a plane.  Same here. Now, as to why I look forward to having self-driving cars.  The main way they will be cool will be making car ownership unnecessary.  You need a car?  Tap a button on your phone, and one drive itself to you.  When you get where you are going, just get out and let it drive away.  Here in San Francisco, parking is a huge pain, you can spend 10 minutes driving somewhere and then half an hour finding a place to park and then walking from that place. You can do that with a cab, but you are having to pay for a human driver, and that's a lot more expensive.  Self driving cars will make it much more feasable to not own a car, or to have neighborhood car sharing.  The end result is we could have a whole lot less cars, since the ones that exist will be in use most of the time rather than sitting there parked taking up space.",
