            "html": "<p class=\"q-text qu-display--block qu-wordBreak--break-word qu-textAlign--start\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 1em; overflow-wrap: anywhere; direction: ltr;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">I have gotten into a self-driving car, several times; sometimes I was in the front seat ready to overpower the servo steering if I didn’t like what the car did, other times I was in the back seat with my head in a laptop trying to figure out why the car was doing what it was doing at any given time. Driving speeds were pretty low, I think we topped at 45 mph (except that one time we took the car on a dried lakebed and hit over 70mph, but that’s a whole other story). The only reason I did that was because I had programmed part of the so-called AI (route planner, trajectory planner and traffic arbitration logic), and I knew the internals of the sensor fusion software, the safety interlocks and the quality of the differential GPS signal at any given time. If anything looked even remotely wrong, the big red button would be pressed and no more self-driving car.</span></p> <p class=\"q-text qu-display--block qu-wordBreak--break-word qu-textAlign--start\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 0px; overflow-wrap: anywhere; direction: ltr;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">I don’t know if I would be as brave on a car someone else programmed - not because I’m smarter, more like the devil you know versus the devil you don’t know kind of thing. Also, I would like to see some engineering assessment of the vehicle and results of third party systematic tests before making a decision, something other than “it’s driven so many hours and nothing bad happened”. I have also noticed that I more suspicious of self-driving cars than others, so even though I may be willing to ride in one, I am not sure about having one my kids be a passenger in one.</span></p>",
